english:
  title: Postscript to Poems and Writings on the Jeongdang Plum
  author: Kim Il-son
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Years ago, when I wandered the lands beyond the mountains, I passed through Danseok Temple on my way to view Mount Duryoo. Within the temple stood an ancient pavilion, and before it grew two plum trees, each more than a man's height tall. Below them lay a withered stump, still half a foot high and clinging to life. The monks called it the Jeongdang Plum. When I asked why it bore such a name, they told me that Kang Tong-jeong had planted it with his own hands in youth. Later, he passed the civil service examination and rose to the position of Jeongdang Scholar-official, and so the tree took his name. More than a hundred years have passed since Jeongdang departed this world, and the plum tree too has succumbed to age. Yet his great-grandson, Yong-hyu, following the command of his grandfather Jinsan-gun, came seeking this legacy. Moved by what he found, he planted new roots beside the old. Now, ten years hence, the Jeongdang line is not alone in bearing descendants—the plum tree has flourished with them.

    It was early summer then, and no fragrant whisper lingered in the air. I reached up to pluck the tender branches and tasted the green fruit, and at the monk's urging, I recorded this as a tale to be remembered. Eight years later, Yong-hyu ascended to the position of Minister in the Political Bureau, while I became a clerk in the Court of Rites. We saw each other daily in the palace halls. One day he showed me verses and writings about the Jeongdang Plum composed by various gentlemen, and pressed me to append my words to theirs.

    I reflected thus: In heaven and earth, not a single blade of grass, not the meanest tree escapes the number inscribed upon it. Their flourishing and decay, their fortune and loss—all are dispensed by the hand of Creation. Though they rest in human keeping, there remains something beyond human reckoning. The ignorant steal from Creation's abundance and call it their own. Once, in the Tang Dynasty, Li Wenrao spent his lifetime gathering flowers and stones from distant lands to fill his garden at Pingquan. He declared: "I have built Pingquan to honor my ancestors' wishes. Not one flower, not one stone shall my descendants allow to perish. Only when hillsides become valleys and valleys become hills shall this end." Yet his grandson, Yan-gu, met his doom because of a single stone, struck down by the general Zhang Quanyi. Before the hills and valleys could truly shift, Pingquan had already lost its master. That man, dwelling in wealth and power, harbored in his breast a base and grasping spirit, which extended even to his flowers and trees. In this way he sought to honor his ancestors and leave a legacy to his sons. Can such a man be called one who understands Creation's way?

    When Tong-jeong dwelt at Danseok Temple, he was but a humble scholar, at ease beyond the dust of the world. He tended the plum and departed as one leaving behind a trifle, entrusting its fate to the temple monks—not as an inheritance for his descendants. Yet when he rose to the high office of Jeongdang Scholar, the monks seized upon his name and affixed it to the tree, thus transmitting its fragrant fame almost by chance. That a worthy great-grandson came to tend and protect it further—this too was not through Tong-jeong's instruction. How strange it is! The calculating Li Wenrao could not preserve Pingquan for his sons, while the unattached Tong-jeong effortlessly left his plum thriving in a remote temple. Creation itself abhors the grasping heart.

    Alas—the man has gone, but the poem remains; the deed has passed, yet the name endures. In that isolated valley of wilderness, within the desolate courtyard of a forgotten temple, the withered root and the new branch face each other in cold shadow. What feelings must stir in the hearts of his descendants? This is why, having nurtured the tree anew, they seek verses to express their hearts. I see in Minister Yong-hyu a reverence for his ancestors that never falters. He has gathered the writings of his forebears and distributed them among scholars, fearing the fragrance might not spread widely enough. The new poems on the plum tree from the robes of office grow so numerous they begin to fill scrolls—all this devotion rendered unto ancestors, not claiming any as their own. Yet truly they do cherish this tree, and none could love it more.

    Among all plants worthy of cultivation, one is not singular. But Tong-jeong, from his youth, possessed an affinity for the plum and thus planted it. Jinsan-gun was revered as a master of refined learning; his elder brother, Gyeong-u, compiled the Record of Flower Cultivation and ranked the plum foremost in his classifications. Minister Yong-hyu has inherited this esteem from his ancestors, tending this plum with anxious care, ever fearful of its decline. In such dedication to beauty and elegance, his family's legacy is made clear.

    As for one such as I—bound to meager office and meager salary, my dreams ever wandering homeward—should I someday obtain leave to return south, I shall surely seek out Danseok Temple once more. When the moon sets and the stars of Shen appear in the sky, I will compose a verse upon the plum's sparse shadows. And I shall ask the temple monks: from this day forward, let this tree be called the Jeongdang Plum.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Jeongdang (政堂) was a scholarly administrative position in the Goryeo dynasty.
  - key: ''
    value: Li Wenrao (李德裕, 787-849) was a famous Tang dynasty official known for his elaborate garden at Pingquan; this allusion illustrates the Buddhist principle that possessiveness leads to loss.
  - key: ''
    value: The Jinsan-gun (晉山君) was likely a local nobleman or official in the region where the temple stood.
  - key: ''
    value: The appearance of the stars of Shen and the setting moon indicates late night, a time traditionally associated with reflection and melancholy in East Asian poetry.
